{
  "duration": 77.23,
  "text": "Avogadro discovered something incredible. At the same temperature and pressure, equal volumes of any gas contain the same number of molecules. That means one mole of any gas takes up the same volume. At room temperature and pressure, that's 24 dim cubed. At STP, it's 22.4 dim cubed. The formula, volume equals moles times molar volume. V equals N times 24. Or rearrange. N equals V divided by 24. Example, what volume does 0.5 moles of oxygen occupy at RTP? Volume equals 0.5 times 24. That's 12 dim cubed. Done. Harder one. What mass of CO2 occupies 6 dim cubed at RTP? Step 1, moles. 6 divided by 24 equals 0.25 moles. Step 2, mass 0.25 times 44 equals 11 grams. See how it connects? The mole links mass, volume, and concentration. That's three formulas. N equals M over M. N equals C times V. N equals volume over 24. The mole is always in the middle.",
